{
  "doc_id": "49550",
  "text": "In SCLC, we found that hamartin expression correlates with p-TSC2 and may point towards a disruption of the hamartin-tuberin complex, which is accompanied by phosphorylation of tuberin and activation (i.e. phosphorylation) of mTOR. Moreover, the expression of hamartin correlated with that of nuclear p-mTOR (CC = 0.405; p = 0.007) suggesting that hamartin may be an interesting surrogate marker for mTOR related signaling. The immunohistochemical characterization of signaling pathways during the routine histological workup of specimens would greatly facilitate the selection of individualized therapeutic regimens that are currently arising by the availability of new molecular targets such as mTOR inhibitors [CITATION_1] .",
